{
  "texts": [
    "Counterfactual inferences can be more or less general, where one can distinguish between parameterized and exogenous variable counterfactual inferences (Pearl, 2009; Halpern, 2016).",
    "Parameterized counterfactual inferences involve changing specific variables within a model, such as \"What would happen to the period of this spring-mass system if we changed the spring constant?\".",
    "Exogenous variable counterfactual inferences involve changing external variables that impact the system, such as \"What would happen to this spring-mass system if the spring breaks?",
    "In this section we discuss how to operationalize the framework described in the previous section into concrete tests to measure scientific understanding.",
    "Understanding can be of a concrete phenomenon (e.g., a pendulum of 5 m length, 2 kg weight, etc.)"
  ]
}